#### Undocumented endpoints

[](https://github.com/knocklabs/knock-node#undocumented-endpoints)
To make requests to undocumented endpoints, you can use `client.get`, `client.post`, and other HTTP verbs. Options on the client, such as retries, will be respected when making these requests.

await client.post('/some/path', {
  body: { some_prop: 'foo' },
  query: { some_query_arg: 'bar' },
});

#### Undocumented request params

[](https://github.com/knocklabs/knock-node#undocumented-request-params)
To make requests using undocumented parameters, you may use `// @ts-expect-error` on the undocumented parameter. This library doesn't validate at runtime that the request matches the type, so any extra values you send will be sent as-is.

client.workflows.trigger({
  // ...
  // @ts-expect-error baz is not yet public
  baz: 'undocumented option',
});

For requests with the `GET` verb, any extra params will be in the query, all other requests will send the extra param in the body.

If you want to explicitly send an extra argument, you can do so with the `query`, `body`, and `headers` request options.

#### Undocumented response properties

[](https://github.com/knocklabs/knock-node#undocumented-response-properties)
To access undocumented response properties, you may access the response object with `// @ts-expect-error` on the response object, or cast the response object to the requisite type. Like the request params, we do not validate or strip extra properties from the response from the API.

### Customizing the fetch client

[](https://github.com/knocklabs/knock-node#customizing-the-fetch-client)
By default, this library expects a global `fetch` function is defined.

If you want to use a different `fetch` function, you can either polyfill the global:

import fetch from 'my-fetch';

globalThis.fetch = fetch;

Or pass it to the client:

import Knock from '@knocklabs/node';
import fetch from 'my-fetch';

const client = new Knock({ fetch });

### Fetch options

[](https://github.com/knocklabs/knock-node#fetch-options)
If you want to set custom `fetch` options without overriding the `fetch` function, you can provide a `fetchOptions` object when instantiating the client or making a request. (Request-specific options override client options.)

import Knock from '@knocklabs/node';

const client = new Knock({
  fetchOptions: {
    // `RequestInit` options
  },
});

#### Configuring proxies

[](https://github.com/knocklabs/knock-node#configuring-proxies)
To modify proxy behavior, you can provide custom `fetchOptions` that add runtime-specific proxy options to requests:

[![Image 3](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/stainless-api/sdk-assets/refs/heads/main/node.svg)](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/stainless-api/sdk-assets/refs/heads/main/node.svg)**Node**[[docs](https://github.com/nodejs/undici/blob/main/docs/docs/api/ProxyAgent.md#example---proxyagent-with-fetch)]

import Knock from '@knocklabs/node';
import * as undici from 'undici';

const proxyAgent = new undici.ProxyAgent('http://localhost:8888');
const client = new Knock({
  fetchOptions: {
    dispatcher: proxyAgent,
  },
});

[![Image 4](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/stainless-api/sdk-assets/refs/heads/main/bun.svg)](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/stainless-api/sdk-assets/refs/heads/main/bun.svg)**Bun**[[docs](https://bun.sh/guides/http/proxy)]

import Knock from '@knocklabs/node';

const client = new Knock({
  fetchOptions: {
    proxy: 'http://localhost:8888',
  },
});

[![Image 5](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/stainless-api/sdk-assets/refs/heads/main/deno.svg)](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/stainless-api/sdk-assets/refs/heads/main/deno.svg)**Deno**[[docs](https://docs.deno.com/api/deno/~/Deno.createHttpClient)]

